I have joined my colleagues in seeking answers from the administration on what its strategy and plans are for the region. I will seek those answers, hold the administration accountable for its actions and ensure the women and men in our military are not needlessly put at risk.
The U.S. still holds a supreme military edge over Iran and has the ability to play the long game in the region. We should not undermine any diplomatic edge we currently hold.
The U.S. needs to consider that our host country, Iraq, does not want to be in the middle of a proxy fight between our country and Iran. That fight places our fight against ISIS at risk.

I have low expectations that this administration can satisfy Congress‚Äô legitimate questions about the imminent threat it says precipitated US airstrikes, what its regional strategy is, or what legal authority it used;

In three years of this administration, Middle East policy has gone from having an international nuclear deal with Iran that had stopped Iran from developing nuclear weapons to now, what some call the brink of war.

The administration can try to make the argument there was some imminent threat that warranted the airstrikes, but it has shared no evidence with Congress, has ratcheted up tensions with Iran, and done so without any legal authority that I can find.

For all the talk the President makes about getting out of the Middle East, his actions continue to foreshadow even more involvement in the region, including the most recent airstrikes followed by a deployment of 3,500 more U.S. personnel.
